WEBVTT

1
00:01:36.841 --> 00:01:38.001
[JIG PLAYING ON FIDDLE]

2
00:01:38.162 --> 00:01:40.081
[CROWD CHATTERING AND LAUGHING]

3
00:01:40.281 --> 00:01:42.200
[CROWD CHEERING]

4
00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:56.639
[CROWD CHEERING]

5
00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:12.839
[CROWD LAUGHING]

6
00:02:13.599 --> 00:02:16.159
MAN 1: Let's hear a few words
from our fair hostess.

7
00:02:16.319 --> 00:02:18.678
Come on, Shannon. Give us a speech.

8
00:02:18.839 --> 00:02:21.318
<i>CROWD [IN UNISON]:
Speech! Speech! Speech!</i>

9
00:02:21.479 --> 00:02:24.717
Uh, yes, of course.

10
00:02:24.998 --> 00:02:28.117
On behalf of the Blake clan,
myself included...

11
00:02:28.278 --> 00:02:30.597
...I want to welcome
all of our mighty competitors...

12
00:02:30.758 --> 00:02:33.318
...to the first ever
Loch Ness Highland Games.

13
00:02:33.478 --> 00:02:35.157
CROWD:
Hooray!

14
00:02:35.318 --> 00:02:38.837
SHANNON: And I want to thank all of
the volunteers who helped us transform...

15
00:02:38.998 --> 00:02:43.396
...the ancient grounds of Blake Castle
into a first-rate tournament field.

16
00:02:43.558 --> 00:02:45.956
Now the Blakes
can finally be known for something...

17
00:02:46.117 --> 00:02:48.596
...besides getting themselves
into trouble, eh, Shannon?

18
00:02:48.757 --> 00:02:50.796
I just hope
we can survive the embarrassment...

19
00:02:50.957 --> 00:02:53.716
...should you be
our winning contestant, Angus Haggart.

20
00:02:53.877 --> 00:02:55.476
CROWD: Ha-ha-ha.
MAN 2: She got you, Angus.

21
00:02:55.637 --> 00:02:57.396
That's my brother you be speaking to.

22
00:02:57.557 --> 00:03:00.036
If anyone's got claim
to be embarrassed by him, it's me.

23
00:03:00.197 --> 00:03:03.235
Aye, then. What do you say
we start the games early?

24
00:03:03.396 --> 00:03:06.275
- Biggest splash wins.
- Oh, you're on.

25
00:03:06.436 --> 00:03:08.154
Wait! No!

26
00:03:08.356 --> 00:03:10.074
[CROWD CHEERS]

27
00:03:13.395 --> 00:03:14.754
[CROWD LAUGHS]

28
00:03:14.915 --> 00:03:16.794
Please, guys, get back in the boat.

29
00:03:16.955 --> 00:03:20.634
What? Afraid the Legend of the Loch might
be coming back for a midnight snack?

30
00:03:20.795 --> 00:03:22.074
SHANNON:
This isn't funny.

31
00:03:22.235 --> 00:03:24.274
ANGUS:
If I didn't know any better, Shannon Blake...

32
00:03:24.435 --> 00:03:28.274
...I'd be thinking you believed
in the Loch Ness Monster.

33
00:03:37.635 --> 00:03:39.993
Aah! What the...?

34
00:03:43.194 --> 00:03:44.993
No, it cannot be.

35
00:03:45.593 --> 00:03:47.473
[ALL SCREAMING]

36
00:03:49.633 --> 00:03:53.072
Colin! Angus! Get out of the water now!

37
00:03:55.633 --> 00:03:57.111
Hold on!

38
00:03:59.793 --> 00:04:02.832
We're double-anchored. She won't move
an inch until we hoist them up.

39
00:04:04.992 --> 00:04:06.391
[ALL SCREAMING]

40
00:04:15.592 --> 00:04:16.991
Brace yourselves!

41
00:04:29.630 --> 00:04:32.030
MAN 3: I don't understand what happened.
MAN 4: What was that?

42
00:04:32.191 --> 00:04:34.709
MAN 3: What happened?
MAN 5: I don't know what to think.

43
00:04:34.870 --> 00:04:38.029
- Are you all right, Shannon?
- MAN 6: Silence!

44
00:04:39.471 --> 00:04:43.469
For a thousand years
it has swam in the shadows below.

45
00:04:43.630 --> 00:04:45.388
[THUNDER CRASHES]

46
00:04:45.590 --> 00:04:50.228
DUNCAN: You have disturbed the spirit
that haunts these waters.

47
00:04:50.390 --> 00:04:55.268
Too afraid to sleep at night?
Trembling in your beds with fright?

48
00:04:55.429 --> 00:04:58.308
'Tis not the darkness drawing near...

49
00:04:58.469 --> 00:05:01.188
...but the Loch Ness Monster
you should fear.

50
00:05:01.469 --> 00:05:02.508
[THUNDER CRASHES]

51
00:05:22.147 --> 00:05:23.146
[CAR APPROACHING]

52
00:05:23.308 --> 00:05:24.466
[GRUNTS]

53
00:05:25.987 --> 00:05:28.106
DAPHNE:
Ah, how beautiful.

54
00:05:28.267 --> 00:05:31.426
The Scottish countryside
is so lush and green.

55
00:05:31.587 --> 00:05:34.826
FRED:
Yeah. Just like a giant golf course.

56
00:05:36.067 --> 00:05:39.666
Jinkies, Daphne.
It must be exciting to visit Blake Castle...

57
00:05:39.826 --> 00:05:42.266
...the ancient home
of your Scottish ancestors.

58
00:05:42.427 --> 00:05:45.385
DAPHNE: It sure is. And I can't wait
to help my cousin Shannon...

59
00:05:45.546 --> 00:05:47.625
...host the Loch Ness Highland Games.

60
00:05:47.786 --> 00:05:50.545
Oh, I even accessorized
for the occasion. Look.

61
00:05:50.706 --> 00:05:53.105
I'm planning to wear this
for the opening ceremonies...

62
00:05:53.265 --> 00:05:55.705
...in honor of the Blakes of Loch Ness.

63
00:05:55.866 --> 00:05:58.504
Like, it's not the Blakes of Loch Ness
I'm worried about.

64
00:05:58.665 --> 00:06:02.664
Are you, by chance, referring
to the legend of the Loch Ness Monster?

65
00:06:02.825 --> 00:06:05.063
Monster?

66
00:06:05.225 --> 00:06:07.424
Yeah. And, like,
why are we going to some place...

67
00:06:07.585 --> 00:06:09.743
...that's already got
a monster named after it?

68
00:06:09.904 --> 00:06:11.464
Makes no sense.

69
00:06:11.625 --> 00:06:16.103
Legend of the Loch. Get real.
It's just another big fake, right, Velma?

70
00:06:16.264 --> 00:06:17.863
I'm not so sure about that.

71
00:06:18.024 --> 00:06:21.783
Jeepers! You believe
in the Loch Ness Monster, Velma?

72
00:06:21.943 --> 00:06:26.263
- Like, that makes three of us.
- Yeah. One, two, three.

73
00:06:26.424 --> 00:06:28.982
Well, I believe it's a mystery.

74
00:06:29.143 --> 00:06:30.943
This monster is different.

75
00:06:31.104 --> 00:06:34.062
There have been over 2000
Loch Ness Monster sightings...

76
00:06:34.223 --> 00:06:36.782
<i>...dating all the way back to 540 A.D.</i>

77
00:06:36.943 --> 00:06:40.382
<i>- That's almost 1500 years ago.
- SHAGGY: Zoinks! Like, a monster...</i>

78
00:06:40.543 --> 00:06:43.662
...that's been scaring people
for more than a thousand years.

79
00:06:43.823 --> 00:06:47.262
DAPHNE: Don't worry, Shaggy,
Loch Ness has miles of shoreline...

80
00:06:47.423 --> 00:06:50.861
...and I bet Shannon knows
a lot of good places to have a beach party.

81
00:06:51.022 --> 00:06:53.581
Beach party? Hear that, Scoob?

82
00:06:53.741 --> 00:06:56.900
We can have a clambake
with the clan Blake. Ha, ha.

83
00:06:57.061 --> 00:06:59.181
Yeah, clambake. Ha, ha.

84
00:06:59.342 --> 00:07:00.581
[GPS BEEPING]

85
00:07:00.741 --> 00:07:03.100
That's it, gang. Loch Ness, dead ahead.

86
00:07:04.661 --> 00:07:07.260
SHAGGY:
Like, did you have to say "dead"?

87
00:07:18.860 --> 00:07:21.739
Wow, this fog is as thick as pea soup.

88
00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:24.659
Oh, boy, pea soup.

89
00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:27.979
Come back, Scoob.
It's just a figure of speech.

90
00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:30.098
[SCOOBY HUMMING]

91
00:07:38.299 --> 00:07:39.298
Huh?

92
00:07:39.499 --> 00:07:41.178
[YELPS]

93
00:07:45.058 --> 00:07:47.377
What's the matter, old buddy?

94
00:07:47.818 --> 00:07:49.818
Monster. Monster!

95
00:07:49.978 --> 00:07:52.817
Monster? Like, don't tell me.
I don't wanna know.

96
00:07:53.018 --> 00:07:54.017
[CREATURE MOANS]

97
00:07:54.178 --> 00:07:56.377
- Man! What is that?
- What in the world?

98
00:07:59.258 --> 00:08:01.216
Can we get closer?

99
00:08:01.377 --> 00:08:02.856
Freddie! The road!

100
00:08:03.017 --> 00:08:04.416
[ALL SCREAMING]

101
00:08:10.737 --> 00:08:14.655
When I said get closer,
this isn't exactly what I meant.

102
00:08:14.816 --> 00:08:17.096
Did we just see what I think we saw?

103
00:08:17.256 --> 00:08:20.335
Whatever it was, it's gone now.

104
00:08:21.376 --> 00:08:25.336
Come on, gang. This loch water
could shrink my genuine vinyl upholstery.

105
00:08:26.616 --> 00:08:28.175
[GASPS]

106
00:08:29.776 --> 00:08:33.135
Jeepers. Guys, look, I think we're here.

107
00:08:33.296 --> 00:08:35.455
There's Blake Castle.

108
00:08:35.616 --> 00:08:37.535
[ALL MURMURING]

109
00:08:42.575 --> 00:08:46.214
Oh, I just got this baby hot-waxed.

110
00:08:49.455 --> 00:08:53.333
Wow, look at all those tents.
I wonder if there's a circus in town.

111
00:08:53.494 --> 00:08:56.413
That's the sports field
for the Highland games...

112
00:08:56.574 --> 00:08:59.973
...a competition featuring
traditional Scottish sporting events.

113
00:09:00.134 --> 00:09:01.133
[BLOWS WHISTLE]

114
00:09:01.294 --> 00:09:02.333
[COMPETITOR GRUNTS]

115
00:09:05.413 --> 00:09:07.933
Like, who's ever heard
of the telephone-pole pitch?

116
00:09:08.094 --> 00:09:09.453
Huh?

117
00:09:09.614 --> 00:09:12.852
FRED: That's the caber toss, Shaggy.
It's a test of strength and skill.

118
00:09:13.013 --> 00:09:16.332
When they invent a game that tests
eating and sleeping, let us know.

119
00:09:16.493 --> 00:09:18.492
[SHAGGY & SCOOBY CHUCKLE]

120
00:09:18.653 --> 00:09:22.691
The tent colors work for me,
but that crashed sailboat totally clashes.

121
00:09:22.852 --> 00:09:24.891
VELMA:
Jinkies! I wonder what happened.

122
00:09:25.052 --> 00:09:27.331
FRED:
Come on, gang, let's go check it out.

123
00:09:30.932 --> 00:09:33.771
- DAPHNE: Shannon!
- Daphne!

124
00:09:35.532 --> 00:09:37.851
- Oh.
- I can't believe I'm really here.

125
00:09:38.012 --> 00:09:40.130
Guys, this is my cousin Shannon.

126
00:09:41.331 --> 00:09:44.250
We should have known
by her great sense of color coordination.

127
00:09:44.411 --> 00:09:47.650
Well, of course. After all, she is a Blake.

128
00:09:48.771 --> 00:09:50.649
Wow, what happened
to your boat, Shannon?

129
00:09:50.811 --> 00:09:53.730
Oh, that? Well, um, you see...

130
00:09:53.891 --> 00:09:55.049
[HORN HONKING]

131
00:09:55.210 --> 00:09:57.129
[PSYCHEDELIC ROCK MUSIC PLAYING
ON STEREO]

132
00:10:00.010 --> 00:10:01.889
Wow, cool ride.

133
00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:03.969
No, no, no, what are you doing?

134
00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:06.968
This whole area
has to be roped off for evidence.

135
00:10:07.129 --> 00:10:09.769
- Not now, Del.
- A friend of yours?

136
00:10:09.930 --> 00:10:11.009
Hardly.

137
00:10:11.210 --> 00:10:13.529
We've... We've got 20 eyewitnesses.

138
00:10:13.689 --> 00:10:17.608
A large wake. Something big,
something really, really big.

139
00:10:17.769 --> 00:10:19.288
[DEL GASPS]

140
00:10:19.969 --> 00:10:23.847
Why can't it ever be something small?
Something really, really small?

141
00:10:25.289 --> 00:10:26.368
- Whoa.
- Unh.

142
00:10:26.529 --> 00:10:27.847
This is major.

143
00:10:28.008 --> 00:10:29.288
SCOOBY & SHAGGY:
Hmm?

144
00:10:29.449 --> 00:10:31.447
Don't you see? It's because of the games.

145
00:10:31.608 --> 00:10:35.407
- All the activity has disturbed the creature.
- Zoinks!

146
00:10:35.568 --> 00:10:37.287
[MAN LAUGHS]

147
00:10:37.448 --> 00:10:41.047
MAN: The only disturbed creature
around here is you, Del Chillman.

148
00:10:41.208 --> 00:10:44.726
Why, my own sons were out there,
and they're not spooked a bit.

149
00:10:44.887 --> 00:10:47.566
- Angus was scared.
- I was not, Colin.

150
00:10:47.727 --> 00:10:49.646
I'll break your neck like that. I...

151
00:10:49.807 --> 00:10:51.446
[BLOWS WHISTLE]

152
00:10:51.607 --> 00:10:54.806
That's enough.
Save it for the games, laddies.

153
00:10:55.207 --> 00:10:59.326
Now, come on, go on down to the track.
Off you go.

154
00:11:00.606 --> 00:11:02.766
But... But, Mr. Haggart, wait.

155
00:11:02.926 --> 00:11:06.845
You are in great danger, sir.
You can't just ignore this.

156
00:11:07.006 --> 00:11:08.165
We could try.

157
00:11:08.366 --> 00:11:10.765
Ugh. You'll see, man.

158
00:11:10.926 --> 00:11:13.884
I told you those games were a mistake,
Shannon.

159
00:11:14.045 --> 00:11:16.244
Now the monster's after you!

160
00:11:16.405 --> 00:11:20.244
<i>[ON STEREO]
Took me a long time to get back on the train</i>

161
00:11:21.125 --> 00:11:24.804
By the way, big party at Stubby's tonight.
Supposed to have a band.

162
00:11:24.965 --> 00:11:28.644
<i>Now I'm gone and I'll never look back again</i>

163
00:11:30.804 --> 00:11:33.563
<i>I'm gone and I'll never look back at all</i>

164
00:11:35.564 --> 00:11:37.723
DAPHNE:
Wow, Blake Castle.

165
00:11:37.884 --> 00:11:40.963
I've waited my whole life to see this.

166
00:11:41.124 --> 00:11:43.963
There's over 800 years
of Blake family history...

167
00:11:44.124 --> 00:11:45.363
...within these walls.

168
00:11:45.524 --> 00:11:48.442
Ours is a rich history
of falling through trap doors...

169
00:11:48.603 --> 00:11:51.322
...finding dangerous secret passageways,
and getting caught...

170
00:11:51.483 --> 00:11:54.522
...in overly complicated booby traps
of our own design.

171
00:11:55.003 --> 00:11:58.041
The one thing we Blakes
have been known for is being...

172
00:11:58.203 --> 00:11:59.602
How shall I put this? Heh.

173
00:12:00.163 --> 00:12:01.361
Danger-prone.

174
00:12:02.523 --> 00:12:03.681
What?

175
00:12:03.842 --> 00:12:06.281
- Stunning architecture. Love the gargoyle.
- Huh? Oh. Uh, nothing.

176
00:12:06.803 --> 00:12:09.282
Despite all these years of misfortune...

177
00:12:09.442 --> 00:12:13.881
...no one at Blake Castle has ever
had any trouble with the monster.

178
00:12:14.042 --> 00:12:16.881
SHAGGY:
Like, that's what I like to hear.

179
00:12:18.042 --> 00:12:20.320
That is, until now.

180
00:12:20.522 --> 00:12:21.721
Like, zoinks.

181
00:12:22.121 --> 00:12:24.520
It actually began just a few nights ago.

182
00:12:24.681 --> 00:12:27.640
<i>I was by myself, down at the boat dock.</i>

183
00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:36.960
<i>All of a sudden, something very big
and very fast came cruising into the cove.</i>

184
00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:40.599
<i>It disappeared below the surface,
and I lost sight of it.</i>

185
00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:48.398
<i>When I fell asleep that night...</i>

186
00:12:48.560 --> 00:12:52.039
<i>...I awoke to the strangest sound
I'd ever heard in all my life.</i>

187
00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:54.038
[CREATURE MOANING]

188
00:13:00.559 --> 00:13:02.478
[THUNDER CRASHING]

189
00:13:04.158 --> 00:13:05.797
[CREATURE MOANING]

190
00:13:05.958 --> 00:13:07.398
[GASPS]

191
00:13:11.558 --> 00:13:12.557
[GASPS]

192
00:13:14.559 --> 00:13:15.757
[SHANNON SCREAMS]

193
00:13:15.918 --> 00:13:18.477
[ROARS]

194
00:13:26.437 --> 00:13:28.476
And then it was gone. Just like that.

195
00:13:28.637 --> 00:13:29.716
[ARMOR CHATTERING]

196
00:13:31.117 --> 00:13:33.355
Come on, you two, out of the armor.

197
00:13:33.517 --> 00:13:35.476
SHAGGY:
Like, ever heard of "Scotland the Brave"?

198
00:13:35.637 --> 00:13:37.635
Well, meet Shaggy the chicken.

199
00:13:38.036 --> 00:13:39.036
Yeah.

200
00:13:39.197 --> 00:13:41.355
[SCOOBY CLUCKS]

201
00:13:41.516 --> 00:13:44.835
Jeepers! So the monster
isn't locked in the loch?

202
00:13:44.997 --> 00:13:48.115
VELMA: Many people claim to have seen
the Loch Ness Monster on land.

203
00:13:48.276 --> 00:13:50.035
When I woke up the next morning...

204
00:13:50.196 --> 00:13:52.554
...I tried to tell myself
that it was only a dream...

205
00:13:52.715 --> 00:13:58.034
Oh, it was not a dream. And last night's
shipwreck was no accident.

206
00:14:05.115 --> 00:14:07.594
It was the great beast of the loch.

207
00:14:07.755 --> 00:14:10.673
Zoinks! Who's the creepy lady
in the beret?

208
00:14:10.834 --> 00:14:12.913
I don't know.

209
00:14:14.394 --> 00:14:19.473
- Everyone, I'd like you to meet...
- Professor Fiona Pembrooke.

210
00:14:19.674 --> 00:14:21.873
Scotland's most accomplished
Loch Ness expert...

211
00:14:22.033 --> 00:14:24.553
<i>...and author of the book
Legend of the Loch.</i>

212
00:14:24.714 --> 00:14:29.752
How marvelous. What a pleasure to meet
someone who's done her proper research.

213
00:14:29.913 --> 00:14:32.832
I read that you're
still trying to prove the monster exists...

214
00:14:32.994 --> 00:14:36.832
...even though it has destroyed your career,
demolished your scientific credibility...

215
00:14:36.993 --> 00:14:38.792
...and devastated you financially.

216
00:14:38.953 --> 00:14:42.112
Apparently, too much research.

217
00:14:43.592 --> 00:14:47.871
Wow, professor, these new pictures
of the Loch Ness Monster are amazing.

218
00:14:48.032 --> 00:14:51.711
I was out on the loch by myself that day
when all of a sudden, there she was.

219
00:14:51.872 --> 00:14:53.591
Right next to my boat.

220
00:14:53.752 --> 00:14:57.391
VELMA: Well after the world sees these,
everyone will believe in the monster.

221
00:14:57.551 --> 00:14:59.910
Ach, I wish it were that easy, dear.

222
00:15:00.071 --> 00:15:01.710
SHANNON:
Dinner is served.

223
00:15:01.871 --> 00:15:04.910
I've prepared a traditional
Scottish dinner for you...

224
00:15:05.071 --> 00:15:07.750
...so you'd all get
a good taste of the Highlands.

225
00:15:07.911 --> 00:15:10.830
And, like, we're ready to start tasting.
Right, Scoob?

226
00:15:10.990 --> 00:15:13.710
- Right.
- We'll be starting with haggis.

227
00:15:13.870 --> 00:15:15.949
A true Scottish delicacy.

228
00:15:16.110 --> 00:15:18.309
SHAGGY:
Wow, like, what's in it?

229
00:15:18.470 --> 00:15:20.829
Oh, it's just a boiled sheep's stomach...

230
00:15:20.991 --> 00:15:24.389
...stuffed with diced liver and kidneys.

231
00:15:38.349 --> 00:15:39.908
[DISH CLATTERS]

232
00:15:42.268 --> 00:15:44.028
Zoinks! It's the monster!

233
00:15:44.188 --> 00:15:46.267
That's no monster, it's a man.

234
00:15:46.429 --> 00:15:48.788
IAN:
Dear me. Terribly sorry about that.

235
00:15:48.949 --> 00:15:51.988
Still, quite a smashing entrance,
don't you think?

236
00:15:52.148 --> 00:15:55.987
Sir Ian, you've arrived.
Welcome to Blake Castle.

237
00:15:56.148 --> 00:15:58.827
IAN: Yes. Please excuse the window,
Shannon, my dear.

238
00:15:58.987 --> 00:16:01.307
I found this caber outside,
and I couldn't resist...

239
00:16:01.467 --> 00:16:04.267
...giving it a good toss,
for old time's sake. Ha, ha.

240
00:16:04.828 --> 00:16:08.346
No, no, that'll be fine.

241
00:16:09.147 --> 00:16:11.586
Everyone, it's my honor to introduce...

242
00:16:11.747 --> 00:16:14.466
...the head field judge
for this year's Highland Games.

243
00:16:14.626 --> 00:16:16.506
VELMA:
Sir Ian Locksley.

244
00:16:16.667 --> 00:16:19.185
Director of the Scottish
Natural History Museum...

245
00:16:19.346 --> 00:16:22.546
<i>...and author of the book
Monster My Foot.</i>

246
00:16:22.707 --> 00:16:25.505
Velma, do you have a book
for every occasion?

247
00:16:25.666 --> 00:16:28.585
- Actually, yes.
- So let me get this straight.

248
00:16:28.745 --> 00:16:31.904
You're a museum director
and a judge for the games?

249
00:16:32.065 --> 00:16:34.944
Now, that's what I call multitasking.

250
00:16:35.505 --> 00:16:37.424
Sir Ian, according to your book...

251
00:16:37.585 --> 00:16:40.304
...you believe the Loch Ness Monster
is all a bunch of hooey.

252
00:16:40.465 --> 00:16:44.464
Yes, yes. Hooey, nonsense,
poppycock and fiddle-faddle.

253
00:16:44.625 --> 00:16:47.543
Now, there you are.
You've got your autograph.

254
00:16:47.705 --> 00:16:49.664
And I've got an entire weekend free...

255
00:16:49.825 --> 00:16:52.144
...from any further mention
of the Loch Ness...

256
00:16:52.305 --> 00:16:55.064
Good gravy!
What in the blazes are you doing here?

257
00:16:55.224 --> 00:16:57.623
Hello, Ian.

258
00:16:58.104 --> 00:16:59.503
You two know each other?

259
00:16:59.664 --> 00:17:01.263
Ian and I were once colleagues.

260
00:17:01.424 --> 00:17:04.943
Colleagues? Hardly.
She was my research assistant.

261
00:17:05.103 --> 00:17:07.702
Aye, before you had me fired.

262
00:17:07.863 --> 00:17:10.022
I was trying to run a museum.

263
00:17:10.183 --> 00:17:12.902
I can't have one of my staff
spending all their time...

264
00:17:13.063 --> 00:17:15.062
...chasing after imaginary monsters.

265
00:17:15.223 --> 00:17:19.621
She's not imaginary, Ian.
We've been through this before.

266
00:17:19.782 --> 00:17:21.902
Well, this should be
an interesting dinner.

267
00:17:22.063 --> 00:17:25.941
I don't think the two of them
will make it past the appetizers.

268
00:17:26.102 --> 00:17:28.141
Now, see here.

269
00:17:28.302 --> 00:17:31.661
Please, both of you,
we're all sharing the castle tonight.

270
00:17:31.822 --> 00:17:35.341
Let's put our differences aside for now.
Have you seen the field, Sir Ian?

271
00:17:35.502 --> 00:17:38.061
- It's fantastic.
- Oh, yes, my dear.

272
00:17:38.222 --> 00:17:41.220
Brilliant.
Reminds me of the games of '74.

273
00:17:41.382 --> 00:17:46.580
That man has absolutely no regard
for true scientific discovery.

274
00:17:46.741 --> 00:17:50.420
Like, the only discovery I'd be interested in
is an all-night pizza joint.

275
00:17:50.581 --> 00:17:52.300
Yeah! Pizza joint!

276
00:17:57.620 --> 00:17:59.539
[GROWLING]

277
00:18:06.140 --> 00:18:08.458
Scoob, with your stomach
growling like that...

278
00:18:08.620 --> 00:18:10.778
...we'll never get to sleep.

279
00:18:16.660 --> 00:18:19.578
Like, how far is it
to the nearest vending machine?

280
00:18:26.499 --> 00:18:28.737
Okay, unless we're completely lost...

281
00:18:28.898 --> 00:18:32.457
...the kitchen should be
right around the corner.

282
00:18:32.898 --> 00:18:34.657
Did I say kitchen? Ha, ha.

283
00:18:34.818 --> 00:18:36.977
I mean, creepy hallway.

284
00:18:37.138 --> 00:18:38.896
Okay, like, maybe it's this way.

285
00:18:39.098 --> 00:18:42.257
- Yikes!
- Zoinks! Like, wrong turn.

286
00:18:42.457 --> 00:18:43.456
[SCOOBY WHIMPERS]

287
00:18:43.618 --> 00:18:45.536
It's okay Scoob, like,
just keep telling yourself...

288
00:18:45.698 --> 00:18:47.816
...there's no such things as monsters.

289
00:18:47.977 --> 00:18:52.056
There are no monsters. There are no
monsters. There are no monsters.

290
00:18:52.537 --> 00:18:53.695
[YELPS]

291
00:18:54.577 --> 00:18:58.056
- What is it, Scoob?
- Monster! Monster!

292
00:18:58.217 --> 00:19:00.216
Like, boy, do I hope you're wrong.

293
00:19:00.777 --> 00:19:02.456
Look. Heh. Look, Scooby-Doo.

294
00:19:02.616 --> 00:19:06.095
It's just a tree branch
knocking against that window. Ha, ha.

295
00:19:06.256 --> 00:19:07.935
That's nothing to be afraid of.

296
00:19:08.096 --> 00:19:10.815
[SCOOBY LAUGHS]

297
00:19:11.696 --> 00:19:14.055
Now, the kitchen's
got to be around here somewhere.

298
00:19:14.216 --> 00:19:15.814
Let's try down this way.

299
00:19:18.616 --> 00:19:20.015
Now, stay close, buddy.

300
00:19:20.175 --> 00:19:21.814
We don't want anything scary
sneaking up...

301
00:19:21.975 --> 00:19:24.334
[STAMMERS]
Ghost!

302
00:19:24.855 --> 00:19:27.774
SCOOBY:
Ghost? Where?

303
00:19:32.934 --> 00:19:34.853
[BOTH LAUGHING]

304
00:19:40.094 --> 00:19:41.413
BOTH:
Huh?

305
00:19:44.134 --> 00:19:45.733
SHAGGY:
Like, run for it, Scoob!

306
00:19:45.894 --> 00:19:47.732
[SCOOBY SCREAMS]

307
00:19:51.933 --> 00:19:53.452
[BOTH PANTING]

308
00:19:53.614 --> 00:19:57.492
We did it, Scoob. Safe and sound.

309
00:19:58.253 --> 00:19:59.292
Like, zoinks!

310
00:19:59.613 --> 00:20:02.291
I think we just
locked ourselves outside of the castle.

311
00:20:02.452 --> 00:20:03.452
SCOOBY:
Uh-oh.

312
00:20:04.212 --> 00:20:08.132
Well, look at the bright side, Scoob.
At least it's not raining.

313
00:20:08.332 --> 00:20:10.091
[THUNDER CRASHES]

314
00:20:13.052 --> 00:20:14.251
Good thinking, old pal.

315
00:20:14.412 --> 00:20:17.531
It'll take more than a rainstorm
to dampen our spirits. Ha, ha.

316
00:20:17.692 --> 00:20:19.531
[BOTH YELP]

317
00:20:49.130 --> 00:20:50.529
[CREATURE ROARS]

318
00:22:03.205 --> 00:22:05.564
[GROWLING]

319
00:22:32.004 --> 00:22:33.923
[ROARING]

320
00:22:46.562 --> 00:22:49.282
Ahh! Like, zoinks! It's right outside!

321
00:22:53.842 --> 00:22:56.281
- It's Shaggy and Scooby.
- SHAGGY & SCOOBY: Huh?

322
00:22:56.441 --> 00:22:58.360
Guys, what happened?

323
00:22:58.521 --> 00:23:02.961
Scooby. Stomach. Bats. Kitchen.
Rainstorm. Chase. Monster.

324
00:23:03.122 --> 00:23:04.921
Yeah, monster.

325
00:23:05.081 --> 00:23:07.240
And I thought we Scottish spoke funny.

326
00:23:07.401 --> 00:23:09.240
They went searching
for a late-night snack...

327
00:23:09.401 --> 00:23:11.040
...and were chased down here
by the monster.

328
00:23:11.201 --> 00:23:12.199
[CAMERA CLICKS]

329
00:23:12.360 --> 00:23:14.480
Well, something made these footprints.

330
00:23:14.641 --> 00:23:16.479
FIONA:
This is extraordinary.

331
00:23:16.640 --> 00:23:19.040
Just what I needed. Fantastic.

332
00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:23.119
Oh, curse me kilts, can't a man get
a decent night's rest without...?

333
00:23:23.280 --> 00:23:24.319
[GASPS]

334
00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:26.159
Oh, dear me. No.

335
00:23:26.319 --> 00:23:30.359
No, not the games field. It's ruined.

336
00:23:30.560 --> 00:23:33.439
Oh, this is an outrage.
Look what you've done.

337
00:23:33.599 --> 00:23:37.718
Like, it wasn't our fault.
It tried to eat us. We barely survived.

338
00:23:37.879 --> 00:23:41.158
Tell me. What tried to eat you?

339
00:23:44.039 --> 00:23:45.038
[BOTH GULP]

340
00:23:45.199 --> 00:23:47.437
Like, the Loch Ness Monster.

341
00:23:47.598 --> 00:23:50.757
For the last time, there is no such thing...

342
00:23:50.918 --> 00:23:53.038
...as the Loch Ness Monster!

343
00:23:53.198 --> 00:23:54.797
[IAN'S VOICE ECHOES]

344
00:23:54.958 --> 00:23:57.917
But, Ian, look. The proof is all around us.

345
00:23:58.078 --> 00:24:02.956
IAN: Miss Blake, I do not wish to spend
one more moment at Blake Castle.

346
00:24:03.117 --> 00:24:05.357
Hey, like, us neither. We'll call a cab.

347
00:24:05.518 --> 00:24:07.516
- Hit it, Scoob.
- Taxi.

348
00:24:11.158 --> 00:24:14.796
There you go, governor.
Step lively. In you go, now.

349
00:24:14.957 --> 00:24:17.036
Boy, vacations never seem to last,
do they?

350
00:24:17.196 --> 00:24:18.195
[SHAGGY CHUCKLES]

351
00:24:18.357 --> 00:24:20.196
Don't forget to write.

352
00:24:25.876 --> 00:24:27.196
Are we there yet?

353
00:24:27.356 --> 00:24:29.595
[SHAGGY & SCOOBY YELL]

354
00:24:30.716 --> 00:24:33.075
Whoa. Quick trip.

355
00:24:33.636 --> 00:24:35.955
SHANNON:
Wait, Sir Ian, wait. Please!

356
00:24:37.395 --> 00:24:41.914
Young lady, you see that you have
the game field in order by opening day...

357
00:24:42.075 --> 00:24:45.794
...or I'll see to it that Blake Castle
never hosts anything larger...

358
00:24:45.955 --> 00:24:48.193
...than a miniature-golf tournament!

359
00:24:48.354 --> 00:24:50.034
Driver.

360
00:24:57.834 --> 00:25:01.713
- Well, that didn't go well.
- I believe you could say that.

361
00:25:05.274 --> 00:25:08.273
- Jinkies!
- What? What is it, Velma?

362
00:25:08.434 --> 00:25:09.472
The footprints.

363
00:25:09.633 --> 00:25:12.832
They don't lead to the loch.
They lead into town.

364
00:25:13.793 --> 00:25:16.592
Why would a sea monster
walk along the road?

365
00:25:17.233 --> 00:25:20.752
Well, gang, looks like we've got
another mystery on our hands.

366
00:25:20.913 --> 00:25:24.671
Only nobody's been able to solve
this one for 1500 years.

367
00:25:24.832 --> 00:25:26.751
Monster or no monster...

368
00:25:26.912 --> 00:25:29.671
...I don't know how we'll ever get
the game field repaired.

369
00:25:29.832 --> 00:25:33.831
Don't give up yet, Shannon.
We just need a little help, that's all.

370
00:25:34.232 --> 00:25:37.631
I've got it! First thing in the morning,
we'll head into town.

371
00:25:37.792 --> 00:25:40.831
I know just the bloke to help us.

372
00:25:51.270 --> 00:25:56.190
Here we are, gang. Welcome to Drumna...
Drummy... Uh, Dramunono...

373
00:25:56.350 --> 00:25:58.230
<i>- Drumnadrochit?
- Gesundheit.</i>

374
00:25:58.391 --> 00:26:00.829
[SHAGGY & SCOOBY LAUGH]

375
00:26:01.910 --> 00:26:04.989
DAPHNE:
Oh, this little village is so darn cute.

376
00:26:05.150 --> 00:26:06.949
Like, total grooviness.

377
00:26:07.110 --> 00:26:09.508
There's a bunch of little shops,
a town square...

378
00:26:09.669 --> 00:26:12.988
...the Loch Ness Monster,
a nice flower garden.

379
00:26:13.150 --> 00:26:14.149
[SCOOBY GULPS]

380
00:26:14.309 --> 00:26:16.388
BOTH:
Loch Ness Monster?

381
00:26:22.629 --> 00:26:25.147
Take it easy, guys. That's no monster.

382
00:26:25.308 --> 00:26:28.067
It's just a big balloon filled with helium.

383
00:26:29.229 --> 00:26:30.227
[SHAGGY CHUCKLES]

384
00:26:30.388 --> 00:26:34.427
- Like, we knew it all along, right, Scoob?
- Yeah! All along.

385
00:26:34.589 --> 00:26:39.427
- ANGUS: Unh. Hold it!
- No, you hold it. I'm holding it.

386
00:26:39.588 --> 00:26:41.267
Come on, lads. Tie her down.

387
00:26:42.108 --> 00:26:44.946
Oops, slipped right out of my hands.

388
00:26:45.627 --> 00:26:49.306
Aah! That's real funny, Colin.

389
00:26:49.948 --> 00:26:52.466
So long, Angus. Don't forget to write.

390
00:26:52.627 --> 00:26:54.546
[LAUGHING]

391
00:26:55.547 --> 00:27:00.705
Eh, it's just a joke, Dad.
Hang on, nitwit, I'm coming!

392
00:27:00.867 --> 00:27:04.066
I asked for jocks,
and you sent me jokesters instead.

393
00:27:04.226 --> 00:27:06.785
Wow, Mr. Haggart,
from the size of that balloon...

394
00:27:06.946 --> 00:27:10.065
...I'd say you must be
the biggest Nessie believer in the world.

395
00:27:10.265 --> 00:27:12.265
[LAUGHS]

396
00:27:12.426 --> 00:27:16.464
Me? No, laddie.
Truth is, I do not believe in her at all.

397
00:27:16.625 --> 00:27:19.224
But the more people that do believe...

398
00:27:19.385 --> 00:27:21.464
...the more money she brings
to my hotel.

399
00:27:21.626 --> 00:27:24.504
- Hmm.
- Very hmm.

400
00:27:24.665 --> 00:27:26.904
Mr. Haggart,
can we have a word with you?

401
00:27:27.065 --> 00:27:29.944
Now, Miss Blake,
what brings you to town, then?

402
00:27:30.105 --> 00:27:31.984
Shouldn't you be out at the games field...

403
00:27:32.145 --> 00:27:34.904
...keeping an eye out for more
of your scary monster sightings?

404
00:27:35.065 --> 00:27:37.423
[LACHLAN LAUGHS]

405
00:27:37.584 --> 00:27:40.943
Laugh if you want,
but there may not be any games at all.

406
00:27:41.104 --> 00:27:45.143
These photos were taken last night,
and the games are tomorrow.

407
00:27:45.824 --> 00:27:49.782
LACHLAN:
Ach, the game fields. That cannot be!

408
00:27:49.943 --> 00:27:52.623
Whether you believe
in the monster or not, Mr. Haggart...

409
00:27:52.783 --> 00:27:54.102
...we're running out of time.

410
00:27:54.264 --> 00:27:57.262
Aye, right you are, lass.
Boys, come quick.

411
00:27:58.183 --> 00:27:59.422
These are for you, mate.

412
00:27:59.583 --> 00:28:02.101
- There you go.
- Like, thanks.

413
00:28:02.262 --> 00:28:04.102
[SCOOBY GASPS THEN GRUNTS]

414
00:28:05.343 --> 00:28:09.701
We've got trouble brewing at Blake Castle.
Brace yourselves, lads.

415
00:28:09.862 --> 00:28:12.661
I'm sorry you've got to see such a thing.

416
00:28:13.662 --> 00:28:15.661
Come on, Colin. Let me see.

417
00:28:15.821 --> 00:28:17.740
[BOTH YELLING]

418
00:28:20.142 --> 00:28:21.661
Hold on!

419
00:28:24.422 --> 00:28:26.780
LACHLAN: Now round up some help
and get down to Blake Castle...

420
00:28:26.941 --> 00:28:29.540
- ...as quick as you can.
- COLIN & ANGUS: Yes, Dad.

421
00:28:29.701 --> 00:28:30.940
Huh?

422
00:28:31.701 --> 00:28:33.180
Whoa.

423
00:28:33.341 --> 00:28:36.220
Stupendous! Tremendous!

424
00:28:36.380 --> 00:28:38.499
Nessie's trying to tell us something.

425
00:28:38.661 --> 00:28:41.619
I've gotta get to the castle.
My monster needs me.

426
00:28:41.780 --> 00:28:45.539
- SHANNON: No, Del. Wait.
- Waiting time is Oversville.

427
00:28:45.700 --> 00:28:49.179
She's trying to talk to me.
And I am ready to listen.

428
00:28:49.340 --> 00:28:52.139
Please, Del, we've still got the games
to think about.

429
00:28:52.299 --> 00:28:55.178
The games?
No, no, no, that's the problem.

430
00:28:55.339 --> 00:28:58.618
If it weren't for those games,
Nessie would be happy and healthy...

431
00:28:58.779 --> 00:29:01.538
...and minding her own business, man.

432
00:29:03.859 --> 00:29:05.778
I've got to get over to Blake Castle...

433
00:29:05.939 --> 00:29:09.857
...before those Haggart hooligans get there
and ruin the vibe, man.

434
00:29:10.018 --> 00:29:12.257
You guys keep on keeping on.

435
00:29:12.818 --> 00:29:15.497
[PSYCHEDELIC ROCK MUSIC PLAYING
ON STEREO]

436
00:29:15.658 --> 00:29:17.657
FRED:
Well, good monster hunting!

437
00:29:20.178 --> 00:29:21.297
DUNCAN:
Don't be a fool.

438
00:29:21.458 --> 00:29:25.577
There's no such thing
as good monster hunting.

439
00:29:26.138 --> 00:29:28.136
Like, words to live by.

440
00:29:28.297 --> 00:29:29.816
Uh-huh.

441
00:29:29.978 --> 00:29:33.136
This is our dockmaster,
Duncan MacGubbin.

442
00:29:33.297 --> 00:29:36.416
Duncan MacGubbin?
I've heard that name before.

443
00:29:36.577 --> 00:29:39.775
You hold the record for the most
Loch Ness Monster sightings.

444
00:29:39.937 --> 00:29:41.655
Aye, that I do.

445
00:29:41.816 --> 00:29:45.535
Forty-one.
Though I take no pride in the fact.

446
00:29:45.696 --> 00:29:48.055
Since you're the dockmaster,
Mr. MacGubbin...

447
00:29:48.216 --> 00:29:50.815
...maybe you could point out
Professor Pembrooke's boat.

448
00:29:50.976 --> 00:29:54.815
- She said we could take it out on the lake.
- That's "loch." Hmph.

449
00:29:54.975 --> 00:29:58.014
Now, there be the professor's craft.

450
00:29:58.175 --> 00:30:00.614
FRED:
Oh, uh, out at the end of the "dake"?

451
00:30:00.775 --> 00:30:02.374
That's "dock."

452
00:30:02.896 --> 00:30:05.734
This Scottish stuff can be complicated.

453
00:30:06.775 --> 00:30:09.174
VELMA:
It's an old fishing boat.

454
00:30:09.335 --> 00:30:11.534
She's nearly as old as myself...

455
00:30:11.694 --> 00:30:13.974
...and twice as leaky.

456
00:30:14.135 --> 00:30:15.973
She'll do you fine.

457
00:30:16.134 --> 00:30:20.853
But I warn you,
do not go looking for trouble's view.

458
00:30:21.014 --> 00:30:25.853
At Loch Ness,
trouble can come looking for you.

459
00:30:28.214 --> 00:30:31.892
Like, he should be writing
scary greeting cards.

460
00:30:33.293 --> 00:30:35.533
SHAGGY:
I sure wish I'd brought along my floaties.

461
00:30:35.693 --> 00:30:36.852
VELMA:
So do I.

462
00:30:37.013 --> 00:30:39.132
There's only four life jackets on board.

463
00:30:39.293 --> 00:30:40.972
Maybe there's more down here.

464
00:30:41.133 --> 00:30:42.372
[GRUNTS]

465
00:30:42.533 --> 00:30:45.611
- It's locked from the inside.
- That's strange.

466
00:30:45.773 --> 00:30:47.732
I guess two of us
will have to stay behind.

467
00:30:47.892 --> 00:30:51.091
You mean split up and search for clues?
I like it.

468
00:30:51.252 --> 00:30:54.051
Shaggy and Scooby
volunteering for shore duty.

469
00:30:54.212 --> 00:30:56.011
Aye, aye, captain.

470
00:30:56.411 --> 00:30:59.531
Hey, maybe Shaggy and Scooby
should take the Mystery Machine.

471
00:30:59.691 --> 00:31:01.530
Good idea.

472
00:31:01.972 --> 00:31:03.170
What?

473
00:31:04.771 --> 00:31:08.850
Don't worry, Fred.
We won't get a scratch on her.

474
00:31:10.571 --> 00:31:12.650
[THUD]

475
00:31:14.331 --> 00:31:17.649
Uh, make that two scratches.

476
00:31:20.410 --> 00:31:23.009
Suddenly this boat seems like
a much safer place.

477
00:31:23.170 --> 00:31:25.129
[TIRES SCREECH & HORN HONKS]

478
00:31:36.609 --> 00:31:40.208
I'm taking her up to full throttle.
Let's see what this baby can do.

479
00:31:40.369 --> 00:31:42.008
Aye, aye, captain.

480
00:31:42.888 --> 00:31:47.528
- FRED: Woo-hoo! I'm king of the lake
- Uh, loch.

481
00:31:48.569 --> 00:31:51.088
Things look pretty clear from up here.

482
00:32:01.648 --> 00:32:03.847
<i>SHAGGY [SINGING]:
You take the high road</i>

483
00:32:04.007 --> 00:32:05.767
<i>And I'll take the rocky road</i>

484
00:32:05.927 --> 00:32:08.286
Like, rocky road ice cream, that is.

485
00:32:08.447 --> 00:32:12.206
Ha, ha.
Hey, Scoob, we going the right way?

486
00:32:13.447 --> 00:32:14.926
Uh-uh.

487
00:32:16.247 --> 00:32:17.806
Oh. Uh-huh.

488
00:32:17.967 --> 00:32:21.605
Great. As long as we follow the road signs,
what can go wrong?

489
00:32:34.366 --> 00:32:38.284
Like, are things getting creepier
and spookier, or is it just me?

490
00:32:38.445 --> 00:32:41.244
SCOOBY:
Uh-uh, me too.

491
00:32:53.085 --> 00:32:55.083
DAPHNE:
Anything coming up on the sonar, Velma?

492
00:32:55.245 --> 00:32:56.283
Are you kidding?

493
00:32:56.444 --> 00:33:00.603
This sonar system is so old,
it couldn't pick up a radio station.

494
00:33:00.764 --> 00:33:04.523
That's strange.
I know her research funding is limited...

495
00:33:04.684 --> 00:33:07.082
...but she's obviously not spending
any of it on new equipment.

496
00:33:07.243 --> 00:33:08.283
[SONAR BEEPING]

497
00:33:08.444 --> 00:33:10.402
Hey, we might have something.

498
00:33:11.284 --> 00:33:14.203
There's a large target
off the portside bow.

499
00:33:16.683 --> 00:33:19.122
Look, something's moving
along the surface.

500
00:33:23.923 --> 00:33:25.722
It's her. She's back!

501
00:33:25.882 --> 00:33:29.282
Freddie, now would be a good time
for one of your famous plans.

502
00:33:29.442 --> 00:33:30.922
FRED:
Uh...

503
00:33:33.282 --> 00:33:34.920
Uh, got it!

504
00:33:35.082 --> 00:33:37.761
Throw all the nets overboard.

505
00:33:37.922 --> 00:33:40.201
Velma, run that line
through the yardarm tackle.

506
00:33:40.362 --> 00:33:41.560
Aye, aye.

507
00:33:41.722 --> 00:33:45.000
You mean, this little boat
is going to catch that gigantic monster?

508
00:33:45.161 --> 00:33:47.480
FRED:
That's plan A.

509
00:33:57.040 --> 00:33:58.600
Looks like you got a bite.

510
00:33:59.880 --> 00:34:02.119
[CREATURE MOANS]

511
00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:04.679
Okay.

512
00:34:06.840 --> 00:34:08.199
ALL:
Whoa!

513
00:34:09.320 --> 00:34:10.598
[ALL YELLING]

514
00:34:17.639 --> 00:34:21.758
- Uh, Freddie, what's plan B?
- Uh, we'll head for the shore.

515
00:34:26.319 --> 00:34:30.517
- VELMA: Forward, Fred. Forward.
- Don't tell me, tell him.

516
00:34:30.679 --> 00:34:31.798
Her. It.

517
00:34:39.998 --> 00:34:41.557
We just lost the engine.

518
00:34:43.198 --> 00:34:44.797
Look out!

519
00:34:51.837 --> 00:34:54.036
SHANNON:
At least we're cut loose from the monster.

520
00:34:54.197 --> 00:34:56.836
Great, we'll call that plan C.

521
00:34:57.317 --> 00:34:58.676
Look, the buoys.

522
00:35:03.036 --> 00:35:04.515
Oh, boy.

523
00:35:04.676 --> 00:35:06.835
DAPHNE:
Here she comes!

524
00:35:10.396 --> 00:35:12.875
- She's gone.
- But gone where?

525
00:35:13.036 --> 00:35:16.635
DAPHNE:
She went under the boat and disappeared.

526
00:35:24.715 --> 00:35:25.914
SHAGGY:
Like, Scoob, old buddy...

527
00:35:26.075 --> 00:35:29.074
...I've got a feeling
we're not in Coolsville anymore.

528
00:35:32.474 --> 00:35:34.074
- Unh.
- Unh. Huh?

529
00:35:35.595 --> 00:35:38.433
Zoinks! Like, I think we're stuck.

530
00:35:40.674 --> 00:35:44.153
Wow, look at the size of that pothole.

531
00:35:45.554 --> 00:35:47.113
Yikes!

532
00:35:48.314 --> 00:35:50.513
[ROARS]

533
00:35:50.674 --> 00:35:52.392
Shaggy! Look!

534
00:35:53.873 --> 00:35:56.392
Okay, I'm looking, but I'm not liking it.

535
00:36:01.513 --> 00:36:03.871
Aw, it's only a little salamander.

536
00:36:04.032 --> 00:36:05.032
[BOTH LAUGH]

537
00:36:06.352 --> 00:36:08.391
[SALAMANDER SCREAMS]

538
00:36:13.352 --> 00:36:14.671
[PANTING]

539
00:36:14.832 --> 00:36:18.991
SHAGGY: Like, wait, Scoob!
We gotta stay with the van!

540
00:36:23.671 --> 00:36:25.390
[SCREAMS]

541
00:36:25.551 --> 00:36:27.510
[SCOOBY WHIMPERING]

542
00:36:27.671 --> 00:36:29.590
[CREATURE GROWLING]

543
00:37:50.786 --> 00:37:52.505
[CREATURE ROARS]

544
00:38:11.865 --> 00:38:14.263
Wow. Like, I think we lost her, Scoob...

545
00:38:14.424 --> 00:38:16.783
...but, heh, heh,
what happened to the road?

546
00:38:16.944 --> 00:38:18.624
And for that matter, the land?

547
00:38:22.544 --> 00:38:24.023
[BOTH SCREAM]

548
00:38:24.184 --> 00:38:28.503
Like, Houston, we have a problem.
Mayday! Mayday! Mayday!

549
00:38:28.663 --> 00:38:30.823
- That sounds like Shaggy.
- Shaggy?

550
00:38:30.984 --> 00:38:35.702
- Where are you guys?
- SHAGGY [OVER RADIO]: Like, incoming!

551
00:38:38.103 --> 00:38:40.982
What the heck?
Somebody get that guy's license.

552
00:38:41.503 --> 00:38:43.382
Doggie license?

553
00:38:48.783 --> 00:38:51.461
Are you sure this is where
you saw the monster, Shaggy?

554
00:38:51.622 --> 00:38:54.061
Hmm, let me see.

555
00:38:59.182 --> 00:39:01.541
Like, zoinks! It's the monster!

556
00:39:02.662 --> 00:39:04.660
Yeah, yeah. This is the place.

557
00:39:04.821 --> 00:39:08.620
DAPHNE: Look. These monster tracks
turn into tire tracks.

558
00:39:08.781 --> 00:39:10.620
FRED:
They sure aren't from the Mystery Machine.

559
00:39:11.261 --> 00:39:15.820
Hmm. Who's ever heard of a monster
with a driver's license?

560
00:39:21.060 --> 00:39:24.379
FRED: Uh, sorry about your engine,
Professor Pembrooke.

561
00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:27.419
- VELMA: And the net rigging.
- And your refrigerator.

562
00:39:27.580 --> 00:39:29.418
What happened to the refrigerator?

563
00:39:29.579 --> 00:39:33.418
- Oh, heh, nothing.
- Yeah, uh, nothing.

564
00:39:33.939 --> 00:39:37.418
FIONA: Don't worry yourselves none.
It was all in the name of research.

565
00:39:37.579 --> 00:39:40.458
And it sounds like
you had quite the sighting.

566
00:39:40.619 --> 00:39:44.258
Sighting? My eyes were closed
the whole time. Ha, ha.

567
00:39:44.419 --> 00:39:46.138
Me too.

568
00:39:46.298 --> 00:39:49.498
Well, at least the games field
is looking good as new.

569
00:39:49.659 --> 00:39:51.898
Guess we owe the Haggart brothers
a hearty thanks.

570
00:39:52.058 --> 00:39:55.817
- Yeah, but where are they?
- Heh, those jokers?

571
00:39:55.978 --> 00:39:58.217
If goofing off
were a Highland games event...

572
00:39:58.378 --> 00:40:01.417
...Colin and Angus would be champions
for sure.

573
00:40:01.578 --> 00:40:04.816
Speaking of goofing off,
where's Scooby?

574
00:40:06.617 --> 00:40:10.216
Like, way to go, Scoob.
Here, let me have a peek.

575
00:40:10.377 --> 00:40:11.856
Okay.

576
00:40:18.617 --> 00:40:19.775
SHAGGY:
Hey, look at that.

577
00:40:19.937 --> 00:40:22.736
There's a groovy ship
way out there on the loch.

578
00:40:22.896 --> 00:40:24.295
SCOOBY:
Uh, Shaggy, look.

579
00:40:24.456 --> 00:40:26.016
[FOGHORN BLARES]

580
00:40:26.177 --> 00:40:27.855
Zoinks!

581
00:40:28.016 --> 00:40:29.895
IAN:
Ahoy, there.

582
00:40:30.296 --> 00:40:33.614
Captain Ian Locksley at your service.

583
00:40:33.776 --> 00:40:36.455
Man, like, that barge is on a charge.

584
00:40:41.975 --> 00:40:43.294
[IAN GRUNTS]

585
00:40:47.215 --> 00:40:50.893
Oh, dear, oh, dear!
I'm terribly sorry about that, Miss Blake.

586
00:40:51.055 --> 00:40:54.254
That's quite all right, Sir Ian.
I'm kind of getting used to this.

587
00:40:54.415 --> 00:40:56.933
Yes, of course. That'll do, then.

588
00:40:57.094 --> 00:41:00.893
Secure the bowline. Anchors aweigh!

589
00:41:04.934 --> 00:41:07.253
Like, with Sir Ian around,
who needs a monster?

590
00:41:07.414 --> 00:41:09.373
Yeah. Ha, ha.

591
00:41:09.533 --> 00:41:12.253
Well, well, well, I should have known.

592
00:41:12.413 --> 00:41:16.572
Sir Ian Locksley,
a Nessie true believer after all.

593
00:41:16.733 --> 00:41:19.612
IAN:
Believer? Ach. Nonsense, Fiona!

594
00:41:19.773 --> 00:41:24.172
I'm here to protect the games field.
I am going to patrol these waters...

595
00:41:24.332 --> 00:41:28.491
...to make sure nothing else
peculiar happens.

596
00:41:28.652 --> 00:41:31.651
Loch Ness is now under my command.

597
00:41:31.812 --> 00:41:33.652
FIONA:
You can't do that.

598
00:41:33.812 --> 00:41:36.091
IAN:
I can and I will.

599
00:41:36.252 --> 00:41:38.771
I hereby declare
that no boat other than mine...

600
00:41:38.932 --> 00:41:41.731
...is to be allowed
in the vicinity of Blake Castle.

601
00:41:41.891 --> 00:41:43.450
FIONA:
Oh, and how could you stop me?

602
00:41:43.611 --> 00:41:46.610
By having
that floating scrap pile condemned.

603
00:41:46.891 --> 00:41:49.530
Now, I suggest you finish your repairs
and be on your way.

604
00:41:49.691 --> 00:41:52.930
Ooh. Blow it out your bagpipe.

605
00:41:53.091 --> 00:41:54.850
IAN:
Why, I never.

606
00:41:55.011 --> 00:41:58.769
This boat's got more surprises in her
than you will ever know.

607
00:41:58.930 --> 00:42:00.969
[EXPLODES]

608
00:42:02.890 --> 00:42:05.689
VELMA:
Uh, Professor Pembrooke?

609
00:42:05.890 --> 00:42:09.009
Perhaps we should go with Sir Ian
to search for more clues.

610
00:42:09.930 --> 00:42:13.929
Brilliant. Perhaps we'll make a believer
out of him yet.

611
00:42:14.090 --> 00:42:16.129
That's it, men. Weigh the anchor.

612
00:42:16.290 --> 00:42:20.568
Zoinks! Like, I think the anchor's
gonna weigh more than usual. Ha, ha.

613
00:42:20.729 --> 00:42:22.568
Yeah.

614
00:42:29.808 --> 00:42:33.047
This sure is impressive equipment.
So multifunctional.

615
00:42:33.208 --> 00:42:35.167
Totally. I've got high score.

616
00:42:36.808 --> 00:42:37.807
[BEEPS]

617
00:42:37.968 --> 00:42:40.527
Hey. What happened to my game?

618
00:42:40.688 --> 00:42:44.327
Um, Fred, I think you were playing
the digital compass.

619
00:42:44.488 --> 00:42:46.646
Well, I still got high score.

620
00:42:47.647 --> 00:42:50.206
I've networked my laptop
into the ship's computer.

621
00:42:50.367 --> 00:42:53.566
This way, I can monitor the sonar
and download the information.

622
00:42:53.727 --> 00:42:55.006
Very well.

623
00:43:02.927 --> 00:43:05.045
Huh? Oh.

624
00:43:05.286 --> 00:43:08.885
Say hello to the Ocean Motion 3000.

625
00:43:09.966 --> 00:43:12.804
With it, we can track
our position by satellite...

626
00:43:12.966 --> 00:43:16.804
...while simultaneously
scanning the contour of the loch floor.

627
00:43:16.965 --> 00:43:20.045
- SHANNON: Ah, look!
- McIntyre, report.

628
00:43:20.206 --> 00:43:23.724
Sir, target spotted
bearing 60 fathoms at 30 knots.

629
00:43:23.885 --> 00:43:26.844
VELMA:
It's nearly 20 meters long.

630
00:43:27.365 --> 00:43:28.404
DAPHNE:
It's gone!

631
00:43:28.565 --> 00:43:31.724
A target that size
surely cannot just vanish.

632
00:43:31.884 --> 00:43:33.523
There must be some explanation.

633
00:43:33.684 --> 00:43:36.524
Whatever it was, it's probably hiding
in an underwater cave.

634
00:43:36.684 --> 00:43:38.643
SHANNON:
Aye, Loch Ness is famous for them.

635
00:43:38.804 --> 00:43:41.723
I wish there were some way
we could check it out.

636
00:43:42.404 --> 00:43:43.843
Speaking of checking out...

637
00:43:44.004 --> 00:43:46.323
[SHAGGY WHISPERS INDISTINCTLY]

638
00:43:46.484 --> 00:43:48.243
[SCOOBY WHISPERS INDISTINCTLY]

639
00:43:48.404 --> 00:43:49.842
Yeah.

640
00:43:52.964 --> 00:43:55.482
Great idea, Scoob.
What a groovy hiding spot.

641
00:43:55.643 --> 00:43:58.002
Nobody will find us in here.

642
00:43:59.683 --> 00:44:03.602
I must say, it looks like your friends
fancy my minisub.

643
00:44:03.763 --> 00:44:05.881
That would be perfect
for exploring the loch.

644
00:44:06.042 --> 00:44:07.521
Would you mind if we borrowed it?

645
00:44:07.682 --> 00:44:10.841
- Do you think you could pilot such a craft?
- Sure.

646
00:44:11.002 --> 00:44:13.681
I drove my van into the loch
just yesterday.

647
00:44:16.482 --> 00:44:19.401
SHAGGY: Scoob, next time
I'm picking the hiding spot.

648
00:44:19.562 --> 00:44:21.441
SCOOBY: Sorry.
FRED: Hang on, folks.

649
00:44:21.602 --> 00:44:23.401
Once the magnetic arm releases us...

650
00:44:23.562 --> 00:44:24.761
...it's splashdown!

651
00:44:25.401 --> 00:44:26.880
[BOTH SCREAM]

652
00:44:29.401 --> 00:44:32.120
FRED:
Whoa, cool.

653
00:44:32.281 --> 00:44:34.399
This is great.

654
00:44:35.681 --> 00:44:37.960
All it needs is a styling green paint job...

655
00:44:38.120 --> 00:44:40.999
...and it'll be the bomb-diggity.

656
00:44:43.360 --> 00:44:46.679
VELMA:
It even has a sonar-activated camera.

657
00:44:47.400 --> 00:44:49.279
SHANNON:
Activating exterior lights.

658
00:44:55.999 --> 00:44:59.638
Now, all we need to do is find the entrance
to the underwater caves.

659
00:44:59.799 --> 00:45:02.078
It's darker down here
than I thought it would be.

660
00:45:08.038 --> 00:45:09.878
Monsters. Monsters!

661
00:45:10.039 --> 00:45:13.637
- Huh?
- Monsters! Help!

662
00:45:13.798 --> 00:45:14.838
FRED:
Look out, Scooby.

663
00:45:14.998 --> 00:45:17.597
VELMA:
It's just a school of eels.

664
00:45:18.558 --> 00:45:20.997
DAPHNE:
Fred, watch where you're going!

665
00:45:21.158 --> 00:45:22.357
I would if I could.

666
00:45:28.597 --> 00:45:30.836
Look, I think we found the entrance.

667
00:45:30.997 --> 00:45:32.996
- Really?
- Really?

668
00:45:33.197 --> 00:45:35.396
VELMA:
It is the cave.

669
00:45:37.636 --> 00:45:39.476
And I thought it would be impossible.

670
00:45:39.637 --> 00:45:42.835
Nothing's impossible when you've got
Scooby-Doo around.

671
00:45:42.996 --> 00:45:43.995
Aw, shucks.

672
00:45:44.157 --> 00:45:45.915
[SCOOBY CHUCKLES]

673
00:45:51.956 --> 00:45:55.314
Is it my imagination,
or are we in shallow water?

674
00:45:56.476 --> 00:45:58.634
Prepare to surface.

675
00:46:03.035 --> 00:46:05.074
[ALL CHATTERING]

676
00:46:07.794 --> 00:46:10.634
- FRED: Hello!
- Please don't do that, Fred.

677
00:46:10.795 --> 00:46:13.114
- Why not?
- I'm afraid something might answer.

678
00:46:13.274 --> 00:46:14.434
[SHAGGY CHUCKLES]

679
00:46:14.595 --> 00:46:16.873
[SCOOBY SNIFFING]

680
00:46:22.194 --> 00:46:25.233
Yummy, bones.

681
00:46:30.794 --> 00:46:31.792
[YELPS]

682
00:46:31.953 --> 00:46:33.032
[WHIMPERS]

683
00:46:33.193 --> 00:46:36.472
Huh? Huh?

684
00:46:36.633 --> 00:46:39.632
Scoob, you okay? Oh, man.

685
00:46:39.793 --> 00:46:41.992
You guys might wanna check this out.

686
00:46:42.153 --> 00:46:45.911
It looks like Scooby found
where Nessie tosses her leftovers.

687
00:46:46.072 --> 00:46:48.671
I think we've stumbled across
a burial ground...

688
00:46:48.832 --> 00:46:51.191
...used by ancient Scottish warriors.

689
00:46:51.352 --> 00:46:53.511
If they buried their dead down here...

690
00:46:53.672 --> 00:46:56.791
...that means there must be
a secret entrance back up to the surface.

691
00:46:56.952 --> 00:46:59.111
SHAGGY:
Hey, guys, ha, ha, check us out.

692
00:46:59.272 --> 00:47:02.110
- We're a couple of brave warriors.
- Yeah.

693
00:47:05.072 --> 00:47:06.950
[BOTH LAUGH]

694
00:47:08.431 --> 00:47:10.550
Hey, gang, take a look at this.

695
00:47:11.471 --> 00:47:14.550
It's a screwdriver.
But what's it doing down here?

696
00:47:15.830 --> 00:47:17.790
FRED:
Maybe they were handy ancient people.

697
00:47:18.310 --> 00:47:20.749
- Freddie.
- What?

698
00:47:21.111 --> 00:47:25.549
What would ancient warriors
be doing with a modern screwdriver?

699
00:47:26.190 --> 00:47:30.068
Uh, guys, if you think that's fishy,
just look behind you.

700
00:47:30.229 --> 00:47:31.269
[ALL GASP]

701
00:47:31.430 --> 00:47:33.349
[GROWLING]

702
00:47:34.629 --> 00:47:38.028
- Jinkies!
- Get to the submarine.

703
00:47:38.189 --> 00:47:40.148
Come on, you two!

704
00:47:55.228 --> 00:47:57.387
- We're trapped, Scoob!
- Oh, no.

705
00:47:57.548 --> 00:48:00.747
I guess the only thing we can do now
is fight our way out.

706
00:48:00.908 --> 00:48:05.466
- Remember, we're brave warriors.
- Yeah, brave.

707
00:48:05.627 --> 00:48:09.706
Like, get ready to taste the steel
of McShaggy and Scooby McDoo!

708
00:48:13.267 --> 00:48:17.266
Well, she tasted it, heh, heh,
and I think she liked it.

709
00:48:17.427 --> 00:48:20.265
VELMA:
Shaggy! Scooby!

710
00:48:20.426 --> 00:48:24.705
Let's get out of here.
This place is a real dive.

711
00:48:53.825 --> 00:48:55.503
The creature is following us.

712
00:48:55.664 --> 00:48:58.543
SHAGGY: Like, take the picture, Velma,
and let's go home.

713
00:48:58.704 --> 00:49:02.223
VELMA: We can't. The sonar camera
is mounted on the front of the sub.

714
00:49:02.384 --> 00:49:05.823
DAPHNE: We'll have to turn around
if we're gonna do a photo shoot.

715
00:49:12.383 --> 00:49:14.982
VELMA:
Head straight up that canyon wall.

716
00:49:16.223 --> 00:49:18.142
[BOTH YELLING]

717
00:49:22.023 --> 00:49:23.822
We just lost our portside sensor.

718
00:49:23.983 --> 00:49:26.022
- Careful, Freddie.
- Sorry.

719
00:49:26.183 --> 00:49:28.942
VELMA: Twenty-five more meters.
It's a straight shot to the surface.

720
00:49:30.822 --> 00:49:32.221
VELMA & SHANNON:
Fred, look out!

721
00:49:32.383 --> 00:49:34.221
I see it.

722
00:49:44.261 --> 00:49:46.221
[ALL YELLING]

723
00:49:54.021 --> 00:49:56.180
- She's gonna ram us.
- Hang on.

724
00:49:57.940 --> 00:49:59.340
[ALL SCREAM]

725
00:50:03.940 --> 00:50:06.819
Like, who knew
you could get airsick in a submarine?

726
00:50:06.980 --> 00:50:08.458
[SCOOBY GROANS THEN BURPS]

727
00:50:12.179 --> 00:50:14.538
Great catch, McIntyre.

728
00:50:17.620 --> 00:50:19.419
[ALL SIGH]

729
00:50:19.779 --> 00:50:22.138
SHAGGY:
Like, now can we go home?

730
00:50:33.298 --> 00:50:36.337
FRED: Gang, with the games starting
tomorrow, we'd better get some shuteye.

731
00:50:36.498 --> 00:50:40.977
SHAGGY: Yeah, like, I'd hate to be tired and
cranky during the monster's final rampage.

732
00:50:41.138 --> 00:50:44.416
We can't go to bed yet.
There are too many unanswered questions.

733
00:50:44.578 --> 00:50:45.737
[RUMBLING NEARBY]

734
00:50:46.298 --> 00:50:49.656
Like, I've got one. What is that noise?

735
00:50:50.457 --> 00:50:53.216
It's coming from inside
the Mystery Machine.

736
00:50:53.897 --> 00:50:55.936
[DEL SNORING]

737
00:50:56.456 --> 00:50:58.016
FRED:
Del?

738
00:51:00.537 --> 00:51:05.216
- I think he's sleeping on your poncho.
- That's okay, he can keep it.

739
00:51:06.496 --> 00:51:07.775
[GASPS]

740
00:51:07.936 --> 00:51:11.855
Oh, hey, guys.
Sorry, I was down here at the castle...

741
00:51:12.016 --> 00:51:14.895
...you know, trying to connect
with Nessie's energy...

742
00:51:15.096 --> 00:51:17.655
...and somebody ripped off my van, man.

743
00:51:17.816 --> 00:51:21.535
- Your van's been stolen?
- From Blake Castle?

744
00:51:21.695 --> 00:51:25.655
Like, wow, and it seemed like
such a good neighborhood.

745
00:51:27.215 --> 00:51:29.534
We've got to solve this mystery tonight.

746
00:51:29.695 --> 00:51:32.214
And I know just the person
to help us do it.

747
00:51:32.375 --> 00:51:36.214
Professor Pembrooke. Come in, professor.
Do you read me?

748
00:51:36.374 --> 00:51:39.533
SHANNON: She shouldn't be out
on the loch alone, especially tonight.

749
00:51:39.694 --> 00:51:42.893
DAPHNE: I hope nothing's happened to her.
FRED: She's probably just out of range.

750
00:51:43.054 --> 00:51:46.372
VELMA: She could be all the way down
at the other end of the loch by now.

751
00:51:46.533 --> 00:51:51.052
- DEL: Maybe she's following the monster.
- Or maybe it's following us.

752
00:51:51.254 --> 00:51:53.053
[CREATURE ROARING
& GANG SCREAMING]

753
00:52:08.013 --> 00:52:09.571
[GROWLS]

754
00:52:14.612 --> 00:52:15.611
[ALL SCREAM]

755
00:52:18.372 --> 00:52:22.850
Oh, yeah? You want some of this?
Come and get it, you overgrown lizard.

756
00:52:23.011 --> 00:52:25.971
Um, technically, Freddie,
the monster wouldn't be a lizard.

757
00:52:26.132 --> 00:52:27.371
Lizards are ectothermic...

758
00:52:27.531 --> 00:52:29.890
...whereas this monster
is clearly amphibious.

759
00:52:30.051 --> 00:52:31.810
DAPHNE:
Not the time, Velma.

760
00:52:40.330 --> 00:52:43.810
[IN BRITISH ACCENT] Hello, governor.
Care for a sweep of the old chimney, then?

761
00:52:43.970 --> 00:52:45.889
[SCOOBY HUMMING]

762
00:52:49.970 --> 00:52:51.889
[GROWLING]

763
00:52:54.569 --> 00:52:56.569
[ALL SCREAM]

764
00:53:02.929 --> 00:53:04.128
[BLEATS]

765
00:53:04.289 --> 00:53:05.408
FRED:
Hold on!

766
00:53:09.888 --> 00:53:11.567
[CREATURE GROWLS]

767
00:53:11.728 --> 00:53:13.647
[ALL SCREAM]

768
00:53:13.849 --> 00:53:16.567
Daphne, I can't see.
Your sweater's in the way.

769
00:53:16.729 --> 00:53:18.127
DAPHNE:
That's not my sweater.

770
00:53:18.288 --> 00:53:19.327
[BLEATS]

771
00:53:19.528 --> 00:53:21.447
[ALL SCREAMING]

772
00:53:22.367 --> 00:53:24.407
SHANNON:
It's a peat bog. You've got to stop.

773
00:53:24.567 --> 00:53:26.007
FRED:
No problem.

774
00:53:35.487 --> 00:53:36.606
[CREATURE MOANING IN DISTANCE]

775
00:53:36.766 --> 00:53:39.046
- Uh, guys?
- She's coming!

776
00:53:39.207 --> 00:53:45.205
This is the moment
I've waited for my whole life!

777
00:53:45.367 --> 00:53:47.285
[GROWLING]

778
00:53:48.566 --> 00:53:50.485
[ALL SCREAM]

779
00:53:57.606 --> 00:54:00.804
I think we need to take a closer look
at this monster.

780
00:54:01.365 --> 00:54:05.644
DAPHNE: Jeepers! This is one sea serpent
that could use some moisturizer.

781
00:54:05.805 --> 00:54:10.324
That's not skin, it's canvas. Grab on.

782
00:54:14.524 --> 00:54:16.003
GANG:
Del's van!

783
00:54:16.205 --> 00:54:18.564
Oh. She's not real?

784
00:54:18.725 --> 00:54:19.843
[SIGHS]

785
00:54:20.004 --> 00:54:21.723
But... My van!

786
00:54:22.884 --> 00:54:26.123
- There's no one inside.
- They must have escaped.

787
00:54:26.563 --> 00:54:28.882
FRED:
Hey, check it out, gang.

788
00:54:29.043 --> 00:54:31.762
Del's treads match
the tire tracks we found earlier.

789
00:54:31.923 --> 00:54:34.763
So someone's been using my wheels...

790
00:54:34.923 --> 00:54:37.202
...to fake us out this whole time?

791
00:54:37.363 --> 00:54:38.642
But this doesn't add up.

792
00:54:38.803 --> 00:54:41.842
Del's van couldn't have chased us
through the underwater tunnels.

793
00:54:42.003 --> 00:54:43.642
Or attacked us on the boat.

794
00:54:43.803 --> 00:54:46.802
And Shaggy and Scooby were chased
by the creature last night.

795
00:54:46.963 --> 00:54:49.361
VELMA:
Before Del's van was stolen.

796
00:54:49.522 --> 00:54:53.282
- This can only mean one thing.
- More than one monster.

797
00:54:53.722 --> 00:54:57.161
So Nessie's still out there. Right on.

798
00:54:57.802 --> 00:55:00.401
Nessie or no Nessie,
this van hoax proves...

799
00:55:00.561 --> 00:55:03.440
...there's somebody behind
at least part of this mystery.

800
00:55:03.601 --> 00:55:05.441
There's only one thing left to do.

801
00:55:05.602 --> 00:55:08.361
[IN NORMAL VOICE] Take a two-week
vacation to a tropical paradise?

802
00:55:08.801 --> 00:55:10.080
[BLEATS]
Bahamas.

803
00:55:10.241 --> 00:55:12.800
Yeah, like, the Bahamas.

804
00:55:12.961 --> 00:55:16.599
No, you chickens,
we've got to head back to Blake Castle.

805
00:55:16.760 --> 00:55:18.839
I've got a plan.

806
00:55:20.440 --> 00:55:24.279
SHAGGY: Really, Scoob, is there anything
we won't do for Scooby Snacks?

807
00:55:27.640 --> 00:55:28.799
Ah.

808
00:55:28.960 --> 00:55:30.159
Uh-uh.

809
00:55:40.079 --> 00:55:43.158
Shaggy and Scooby are in position.
Is everyone else ready?

810
00:55:43.599 --> 00:55:46.637
Sonar's up and running.
Everything is clear outside the cove.

811
00:55:46.799 --> 00:55:48.557
<i>[OVER RADIO]
We're standing by. Over.</i>

812
00:55:48.718 --> 00:55:50.678
<i>VELMA [OVER RADIO]:
Fred, how's the trap coming?</i>

813
00:55:50.839 --> 00:55:52.557
FRED:
Uh, roger that, Mama Bird.

814
00:55:52.718 --> 00:55:56.078
This is Baby Bird, and we do have copy.

815
00:55:56.238 --> 00:55:59.877
We are go. Alpha, Bravo, Charlie.
Baby Bird, over and...

816
00:56:00.038 --> 00:56:03.957
Yeah. Um, hi, it's Del. We're ready, Velma.

817
00:56:04.118 --> 00:56:08.436
Uh-oh, hang on, I think we got a problem.
Fog's rolling in fast.

818
00:56:13.477 --> 00:56:16.316
Uh-oh.
I've lost visual on Scooby and Shaggy.

819
00:56:16.477 --> 00:56:19.596
Velma to Shaggy, come in, Shaggy.
Are you two okay?

820
00:56:19.757 --> 00:56:23.316
Negatory on that, Velma.
We got a major problem down here.

821
00:56:23.477 --> 00:56:25.035
Like, we're all out of Scooby Snacks.

822
00:56:25.196 --> 00:56:27.115
[SCOOBY WHINING]

823
00:56:32.356 --> 00:56:34.275
[BEEPING]

824
00:56:36.715 --> 00:56:39.434
DAPHNE:
Sir Ian, you better come take a look at this.

825
00:56:39.956 --> 00:56:43.154
SHANNON: There it is again.
It's heading right into the cove.

826
00:56:43.676 --> 00:56:47.154
- Good gravy.
- I'll call Velma.

827
00:56:47.995 --> 00:56:50.154
Let's not be hasty.

828
00:56:50.954 --> 00:56:52.994
McIntyre, what's going on?

829
00:56:53.154 --> 00:56:56.593
What? No, you can't do this.
This is mutiny.

830
00:56:56.754 --> 00:56:58.513
McIntyre:
Forgive me, Sir Ian...

831
00:56:58.674 --> 00:57:01.634
...but I've come up with a little plan
of my own.

832
00:57:01.794 --> 00:57:04.953
I intend to capture that creature
and sell it...

833
00:57:05.114 --> 00:57:07.993
...for quite a handsome amount of cash.

834
00:57:08.154 --> 00:57:11.272
Catch it? How are you going to catch it?

835
00:57:11.433 --> 00:57:13.752
The old-fashioned way.

836
00:57:20.393 --> 00:57:22.512
Wow, like, I can't see a thing.

837
00:57:22.673 --> 00:57:25.752
This fog is so thick
you could cut it with a knife.

838
00:57:31.072 --> 00:57:33.111
Hey, Scoob, what do you say
we sit back-to-back...

839
00:57:33.272 --> 00:57:37.191
...so nothing can catch us off guard?
SCOOBY: Okay, Shaggy.

840
00:57:38.792 --> 00:57:41.830
I'd like to see
old Fang Fins try to sneak up on us.

841
00:57:41.991 --> 00:57:43.630
- Right, old buddy?
- Yeah.

842
00:57:43.791 --> 00:57:44.831
[SCOOBY CHUCKLES]

843
00:57:44.991 --> 00:57:47.151
Fang Fins. Ha, ha.

844
00:57:55.550 --> 00:57:58.350
Jinkies! The monster is in the cove.
Repeat.

845
00:57:58.511 --> 00:58:00.229
<i>The monster is in the cove.</i>

846
00:58:00.390 --> 00:58:02.630
Tie off your end, Del. I'm going across.

847
00:58:04.830 --> 00:58:06.069
Hit it, man!

848
00:58:14.189 --> 00:58:15.708
<i>SHAGGY [SINGING]:
Row, row, row your boat</i>

849
00:58:15.869 --> 00:58:16.909
<i>Gently down the...</i>

850
00:58:17.069 --> 00:58:19.028
<i>VELMA:
Shaggy and Scooby, can you guys hear me?</i>

851
00:58:19.189 --> 00:58:20.988
Shaggy here. Who's calling?

852
00:58:21.149 --> 00:58:24.228
<i>It's Velma. Now, listen.
You're right on top of it.</i>

853
00:58:24.429 --> 00:58:25.908
Like, thanks for the compliment.

854
00:58:26.069 --> 00:58:28.788
Hey, Scoob, Velma says
we're right on top of things.

855
00:58:28.949 --> 00:58:31.747
<i>No, Shaggy, listen.
It's really beneath you.</i>

856
00:58:31.908 --> 00:58:35.587
You know, I've always thought
being live bait was beneath us too.

857
00:58:35.748 --> 00:58:39.307
- Me. Me!
- Hang on, Velma. Scooby wants to say hi.

858
00:58:39.468 --> 00:58:42.787
<i>- Wait!
- Hi, Velma.</i>

859
00:58:42.948 --> 00:58:46.107
Scooby, listen.
Your boat is on top of the monster's head.

860
00:58:50.867 --> 00:58:53.906
Velma, like, I think we found the monster.

861
00:58:54.067 --> 00:58:57.306
Hang on, guys, help is on the way!

862
00:58:57.827 --> 00:59:00.626
You heard him, Scoob. Hang on.

863
00:59:00.787 --> 00:59:04.105
- Whoa!
- SCOOBY: Whee!

864
00:59:04.266 --> 00:59:05.706
[SCOOBY CHUCKLES]

865
00:59:05.906 --> 00:59:07.825
[BOTH GRUNTING]

866
00:59:09.866 --> 00:59:11.425
[SCOOBY CHUCKLES]

867
00:59:22.866 --> 00:59:25.984
VELMA: Nice job, Fred.
The monster's trapped in the cove.

868
00:59:26.145 --> 00:59:28.424
FRED: How about that, Velma?
One of our traps worked...

869
00:59:28.585 --> 00:59:31.704
...without some unforeseen detail
going horribly wrong.

870
00:59:31.865 --> 00:59:34.384
<i>VELMA:
Uh, Freddie, look behind you.</i>

871
00:59:34.545 --> 00:59:36.223
Whoa.

872
00:59:39.144 --> 00:59:40.704
[PSYCHEDELIC ROCK MUSIC PLAYING
ON STEREO]

873
00:59:40.864 --> 00:59:44.143
<i>See my face in the town that's flashing by</i>

874
00:59:47.264 --> 00:59:49.863
Watch out, Freddie! He's got a harpoon!

875
00:59:50.664 --> 00:59:51.982
Huh?

876
00:59:52.744 --> 00:59:54.222
Whoa!

877
00:59:54.783 --> 00:59:57.542
<i>I left it all behind
And yet I've traveled far</i>

878
00:59:57.703 --> 01:00:01.302
- Hey, buddy, need a lift?
- How far are you going?

879
01:00:07.782 --> 01:00:09.701
[CREATURE GROWLING]

880
01:00:16.502 --> 01:00:19.701
- Target in range!
- Excellent.

881
01:00:22.821 --> 01:00:24.021
[DAPHNE STOMPS & CAPTOR 1 YELPS]

882
01:00:24.182 --> 01:00:25.460
[SHANNON STOMPS
& CAPTOR 2 SCREAMS]

883
01:00:25.621 --> 01:00:27.100
[CAPTORS GRUNTING]

884
01:00:32.221 --> 01:00:33.860
Fire!

885
01:00:40.140 --> 01:00:41.140
Jinkies!

886
01:00:50.620 --> 01:00:51.778
[ALL GASP]

887
01:00:51.940 --> 01:00:52.979
- Abandon ship!
- Aah!

888
01:00:53.139 --> 01:00:54.579
[IAN YELLS]

889
01:00:58.060 --> 01:01:00.018
Hit the brakes!

890
01:01:06.899 --> 01:01:08.818
- IAN: Help!
- Sir Ian.

891
01:01:08.979 --> 01:01:11.377
Throw me a line! I can't swim!

892
01:01:11.538 --> 01:01:12.737
[IAN GASPING]

893
01:01:12.898 --> 01:01:14.937
We've got to do something.

894
01:01:22.418 --> 01:01:25.496
Hang on, Sir Ian! Help is on the way!

895
01:01:28.458 --> 01:01:29.457
[ROARING]

896
01:01:29.617 --> 01:01:34.816
I don't believe my eyes. She is real.

897
01:01:37.097 --> 01:01:38.176
[METAL CLANGS]

898
01:01:38.337 --> 01:01:40.056
[GASPS]

899
01:01:44.416 --> 01:01:47.416
Who ever heard of a magnet
stopping a sea monster?

900
01:01:47.576 --> 01:01:49.495
SHAGGY & SCOOBY:
Help!

901
01:01:52.336 --> 01:01:54.695
This place is infested with monsters.

902
01:01:59.415 --> 01:02:03.534
Guys, look out! That's where we set the...

903
01:02:03.736 --> 01:02:05.094
...trap.

904
01:02:05.256 --> 01:02:06.734
Oh, no!

905
01:02:13.015 --> 01:02:14.014
[BOTH GROAN]

906
01:02:14.174 --> 01:02:15.894
CREATURE: Roar!
BOTH: Huh?

907
01:02:22.894 --> 01:02:24.373
[BOTH SCREAM]

908
01:02:26.933 --> 01:02:29.292
Scooby! Shaggy! Are you guys okay?

909
01:02:31.613 --> 01:02:35.253
Terrific, considering we're squashed under
the Loch Ness Monster.

910
01:02:35.414 --> 01:02:36.773
BOTH:
Huh?

911
01:02:36.973 --> 01:02:39.012
[BOTH SCREAM]

912
01:02:39.693 --> 01:02:42.692
Monster? I don't think so.
Take another look.

913
01:02:42.852 --> 01:02:44.132
SHAGGY & SCOOBY:
Huh?

914
01:02:47.772 --> 01:02:49.812
SHAGGY:
Colin and Angus Haggart?

915
01:02:50.292 --> 01:02:52.132
BOTH:
Rawr?

916
01:02:52.732 --> 01:02:57.011
So if this one's a fake,
like, what about that one?

917
01:02:57.532 --> 01:03:00.371
Time for this monster to hit the beach.

918
01:03:12.531 --> 01:03:14.929
GANG:
Professor Fiona Pembrooke?

919
01:03:17.171 --> 01:03:18.690
VELMA:
It's all very simple.

920
01:03:18.851 --> 01:03:21.529
Professor Pembrooke
has been behind this all along.

921
01:03:21.690 --> 01:03:25.689
She did a good job.
Scoob and I have been scared all along.

922
01:03:25.850 --> 01:03:28.169
The locked hatch we found
on board her vessel...

923
01:03:28.330 --> 01:03:30.489
<i>...was actually a secret passageway.</i>

924
01:03:30.650 --> 01:03:32.649
<i>FRED: It led to her homemade
monster submarine...</i>

925
01:03:32.810 --> 01:03:34.408
<i>...she kept docked beneath her boat.</i>

926
01:03:34.569 --> 01:03:37.888
<i>VELMA: She'd simply climb down the hatch
and pedal off into the loch.</i>

927
01:03:42.649 --> 01:03:44.928
DAPHNE: That way she could be free
to do her scaring...

928
01:03:45.089 --> 01:03:47.048
...while we all thought
she was on the boat.

929
01:03:47.209 --> 01:03:50.487
But it wasn't Shannon she was after,
or any of us.

930
01:03:50.649 --> 01:03:53.327
It was really Sir Ian's attention
she wanted.

931
01:03:53.488 --> 01:03:56.247
Me? What do I have to do
with any of this?

932
01:03:56.408 --> 01:04:00.167
She was using fake monsters
to get you to believe in a real one.

933
01:04:00.328 --> 01:04:01.567
Exactly.

934
01:04:01.728 --> 01:04:04.446
She wanted you to become
a Nessie true believer yourself.

935
01:04:04.608 --> 01:04:06.887
She couldn't count on Nessie
making an appearance...

936
01:04:07.047 --> 01:04:08.886
...so she created her own.

937
01:04:09.048 --> 01:04:11.366
And she hired Angus and Colin
to help her.

938
01:04:11.528 --> 01:04:13.766
VELMA: Your sons were trying
to scare away the athletes...

939
01:04:13.927 --> 01:04:15.686
...so they could win the games.

940
01:04:15.847 --> 01:04:18.965
- It's not true.
- We don't even care about the games.

941
01:04:19.126 --> 01:04:21.045
We just like a good practical joke.

942
01:04:21.207 --> 01:04:23.886
That monster thing's the greatest joke
we ever pulled.

943
01:04:24.046 --> 01:04:26.805
Aye, lots better than the hedgehog
in the toilet bowl.

944
01:04:26.966 --> 01:04:28.885
The hedgehog in the toilet bowl!
That's a good one!

945
01:04:29.046 --> 01:04:30.085
[ANGUS LAUGHS]

946
01:04:30.246 --> 01:04:34.045
Ugh, I should have prayed harder
for daughters.

947
01:04:34.646 --> 01:04:37.725
It's true. Ian would never have looked
at my new photos...

948
01:04:37.886 --> 01:04:40.084
...unless he came to believe in the beast.

949
01:04:40.245 --> 01:04:42.365
She had to find a way to convince him...

950
01:04:42.526 --> 01:04:46.884
...and the Highland games at Blake Castle
offered her the perfect opportunity.

951
01:04:48.845 --> 01:04:52.004
SHANNON: Ladies and gentlemen,
welcome to Blake Castle...

952
01:04:52.164 --> 01:04:54.803
...and to the Loch Ness Highland Games.

953
01:04:54.965 --> 01:04:59.483
And here to help us kick off the event
is a very special member of the Blake clan.

954
01:04:59.644 --> 01:05:01.884
Please welcome Miss Daphne Blake.

955
01:05:02.044 --> 01:05:03.163
[CROWD APPLAUDING]

956
01:05:03.324 --> 01:05:06.083
Let the games begin!

957
01:05:06.244 --> 01:05:08.283
[ALL CHEERING]

958
01:05:12.083 --> 01:05:13.083
[GRUNTS]

959
01:05:24.483 --> 01:05:26.402
[GRUNTING]

960
01:05:33.322 --> 01:05:34.321
[CROWD CHEERING]

961
01:05:34.482 --> 01:05:36.121
Yay!

962
01:05:36.322 --> 01:05:38.241
[BAND PLAYING
"SCOTLAND THE BRAVE"]

963
01:05:46.761 --> 01:05:47.760
[SHAGGY CHUCKLES]

964
01:05:47.921 --> 01:05:50.841
Like, I never thought being a drum major
could be so major.

965
01:05:51.001 --> 01:05:53.000
[HORN HONKS]

966
01:05:55.520 --> 01:05:57.439
[SURF ROCK MUSIC PLAYING
ON STEREO]

967
01:05:59.080 --> 01:06:02.159
Wow, Fred, like, the Mystery Machine
looks good as new.

968
01:06:02.321 --> 01:06:06.319
Miss Blake! Miss Blake!
I demand to know what's going on.

969
01:06:06.480 --> 01:06:08.479
Sir Ian, what's the matter?

970
01:06:08.640 --> 01:06:11.919
All of you, down to the ship.
That's an order!

971
01:06:12.080 --> 01:06:14.038
BOTH:
Aye, aye, captain.

972
01:06:14.920 --> 01:06:19.318
- Another Pembrooke hoax, that's all it is.
- But where's it coming from?

973
01:06:19.480 --> 01:06:23.558
The sonar camera from the minisub.
It's still transmitting a signal.

974
01:06:23.719 --> 01:06:26.758
But, like, didn't that camera fall off
the submarine and sink?

975
01:06:26.918 --> 01:06:29.238
Something must have passed
in front of the lens...

976
01:06:29.398 --> 01:06:31.358
...and reactivated the sonar sensor.

977
01:06:31.519 --> 01:06:35.157
- Ach, don't be ridiculous.
- Can you get a fix on the signal?

978
01:06:35.318 --> 01:06:36.677
Now, see here.

979
01:06:36.838 --> 01:06:40.437
Quadrant 4. Depth: 104 fathoms.

980
01:06:40.598 --> 01:06:43.397
But that's over 600 feet below.

981
01:06:43.558 --> 01:06:46.517
Much too deep
for any homemade submarine to survive.

982
01:06:46.677 --> 01:06:50.116
It can't possibly be. I mean, really.

983
01:06:50.277 --> 01:06:52.316
Psst. Show him your pictures.

984
01:06:52.477 --> 01:06:57.276
Sir Ian, I don't expect you
to believe me, but here.

985
01:06:57.797 --> 01:07:00.515
Great Scott. These are fantastic.

986
01:07:00.956 --> 01:07:02.796
Miss Blake, I'm terribly sorry...

987
01:07:02.957 --> 01:07:06.715
...but I must resign from my post
as games judge, effective immediately.

988
01:07:06.876 --> 01:07:09.635
Ian, you mean you actually believe me?

989
01:07:09.796 --> 01:07:15.194
Well, ahem, the evidence will, of course,
have to be verified by a third party.

990
01:07:15.356 --> 01:07:17.995
Check it out! These are great.

991
01:07:18.156 --> 01:07:20.834
What are you using here?
Wide-angle lens, right?

992
01:07:20.995 --> 01:07:24.594
Very well, grab your bags, both of you.
We've got a lot of work ahead of us.

993
01:07:24.756 --> 01:07:27.234
Chop-chop.
We don't want to lose her again.

994
01:07:27.395 --> 01:07:29.394
Aye, aye, man.

995
01:07:29.555 --> 01:07:32.954
Well, it looks like you've got
another mystery on your hands.

996
01:07:33.115 --> 01:07:37.114
And none of this would have been possible
without you meddling kids.

997
01:07:37.515 --> 01:07:39.073
We try.

998
01:07:41.154 --> 01:07:42.833
SHANNON:
Well, cousin, I believe...

999
01:07:42.994 --> 01:07:46.513
...we've just given Blake Castle
its wildest story ever.

1000
01:07:46.674 --> 01:07:48.593
DAPHNE:
Thank you, for everything, Shannon.

1001
01:07:48.754 --> 01:07:50.513
Oh, no, thank you.

1002
01:07:50.674 --> 01:07:54.032
None of this could have been possible
without you and your great friends.

1003
01:07:54.193 --> 01:07:56.232
Like, maybe next year
there can be an event...

1004
01:07:56.393 --> 01:08:00.152
...called "the long-distance
Daphne Blake suitcase carry."

1005
01:08:05.792 --> 01:08:08.112
FRED:
Well, gang, that was some mystery.

1006
01:08:08.272 --> 01:08:11.792
I'm actually kind of glad we never found
the real Loch Ness Monster.

1007
01:08:11.953 --> 01:08:14.391
- You are? Why?
- VELMA: I don't know.

1008
01:08:14.553 --> 01:08:17.231
Maybe some mysteries
are just better left unsolved.

1009
01:08:17.392 --> 01:08:19.031
[CREATURE MOANS]

1010
01:08:28.031 --> 01:08:30.910
Huh? Scooby-Dooby-Doo?

1011
01:11:23.700 --> 01:11:25.619
[English - US - SDH]

